segments.text: was from a rather small town background.
His father was a livestock buyer.
He and his wife were from a ranching background.
I was extremely proud when he asked me to help him select some cattle to repopulate his ranch after the drought of the 50s.
He was a rancher.
a very happy experience going entirely over his ranch with him to praise him, advise him about that.
So we had a lot of the same standards and characteristics and he was an inspiration to me.
We've covered your early experiences, your education here at A&M, your ideas about the Corps, military,
leadership.
Is there anything else that you would like to talk about with this interview?
Is there anything that I missed that you think is important to your life, you think important to shaping the type of person you are, and why you became a general?
Well, we haven't said much about the great support I've had from my wife all through the years, or the support and encouragement and inspiration I've gained from my children.
I'd have to say that it sure is easier to achieve if you have a living home life, an environment into which you can effectively sometime retreat, rest, take a change of pace.
associate with people that you know are entirely loyal, loving, and supportive.
So I would have to say that for my immediate family, for my brother, sister, mother, that I've been mighty fortunate in having highly supportive people.
We didn't talk about that a whole lot after we left parents, but I certainly have been one of
the Lord's most blessed people in that way.
Now I've got to go to an award ceremony.
Okay, thank you very much for this interview.
Yeah, it's been fun, an ego trip.
